		<!-- Begin Comments -->
		
		<b>Comment By Valerie Harmd, 9-16-10</b>
		<p>While I am a great admirer and follower of anything Rick Bass writes, I think the headline here "Bigger than Elvis" is way off track.  Elvis' singing and career made him "the king".  The two are not comparable nor in the same league.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Susan, 9-16-10</b>
		<p>Fascinating. What a departure of subject matter for Bass. I'm glad he doesn't feel a need to stick to Western subjects that have made him beloved and famous. Great review. (A note to Valerie: I think "Bigger than Elvis" refers to the Brown trio's fame -- at their peak, they were more famous than Elvis.)</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Rodney, 9-24-10</b>
		<p>Good review.<br />
For clarification, the way I understand it, Bass grew up in the Houston area and later lived in Mississippi working as a geologist before moving to Montana.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 9-27-10</b>
		<p>Rodney,<br />
<br />
You're absolutely right.  Thanks for pointing out my error--I've changed it in the article above.<br />
<br />
And Susan and Valerie, yes, the title was intended to refer to The Browns, who were more popular than Elvis at one point.  I can't think of any writer who rivals Elvis in popularity.<br />
<br />
Thanks, all of you, for reading this and commenting.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Valerie Harms, 9-27-10</b>
		<p>Despite the above comments, I am an expert on Elvis and can firmly state the Brown Trio were never more famous than him.  Your headline was a poor choice, detracts from the book.</p>
		
